A query param doesn&#39;t make endpoint different. Query param can be whatever.

    /list/someObjects?firstId=a&amp;secondId=b

this is a valid path for both of those methods, so which one should it call?
In order to have such type you could do:

    @GET
    @Path(&quot;list/someObjects&quot;)
    List&lt;SomeObject&gt; getSomeObjectsBySecondId(@QueryParam(required = false) Integer firstId, @QueryParam(required = false) Integer secondId);

And inside logic check which one is filled to continue with code execution.

Since the function definition it&#39;s the same. Same name, same nr of arguments and same return value. Java compiles as the same. I would advice you to do this:

```java

@GET
@Path(&quot;list/someObjects&quot;)
List&lt;SomeObject&gt; getSomeObjectsById(@QueryParam(&quot;Id&quot;) Integer firstId, @QueryParameter(&quot;secondId&quot;) @DefaultValue(&quot;false&quot;) boolean isSecondId);

```

This way you can always ask for a the first the list of Object by id like so:
`localhost:8080/list/someObjects?Id=111` and will always use the firstId. If you want to get by the secondId, you can make `localhost:8080/list/someObjects?Id=111&amp;secondId=true`.

Looks like a alternative to your approach. Hope this helps!

